05516nam a22008415i 9780520380981DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020035736  a97805203809817 a10.1525/97805203809812doi  a(DE-B1597)577405  a(OCoLC)1248759178  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS779.46 7aHIS0080002bisacsh1 aGarside, Roger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChina Coup :bThe Great Leap to Freedom /cRoger Garside. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 The Coup -- t1 The Coup -- t2 Why a Coup? -- t2 Totalitarian China: Outwardly Strong, Inwardly Weak -- t3 The Looming Economic Crisis -- t4 No Trust, No Truth -- t5 Who Rules: God or the Party? -- t6 An Environmental Catastrophe -- t7 Coronavirus: Cover-up and Costs -- t8 America and the Fate of Xi -- t9 The Great Unfinished Business -- t3 After the Coup, a Revolution -- t10 Launching the Revolution -- tAfterword: One Life, Two Questions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn expert's take on how a coup in China could launch a transition to democracy. This short book predicts-contrary to the prevailing consensus-that China's leader Xi Jinping will very soon be removed from office in a coup d'état mounted by rivals in the top leadership. The leaders of the coup will then end China's one-party dictatorship and launch a transition to democracy and the rule of law. Long-time diplomat and development banker author Roger Garside draws on his deep knowledge of Chinese politics and economics first to develop a detailed scenario of how these events may unfold, and then-in the main body of the book-to explain why. His gripping, persuasive account of how Chinese leaders plot and plan away from the public eye is unique in published literature. Garside argues that under Xi's overconfident leadership, China is on a collision course with an America that is newly awakened out of complacency. As Xi's rivals look abroad, they are alarmed that he is blind to the reactions that China's actions have provoked from the world's strongest power and its allies. In domestic affairs, Xi's rivals recognize that economic and social change without political reform have created problems that require not just new leaders but a new system of government. Security abroad and stability at home demand a revolution to which Xi is implacably opposed. To save China-and themselves-from catastrophe, they must remove him and end the dictatorship he is determined to defend. But their will and capacity to do so depend crucially on how liberal democracies act. Garside's scenario shows America leading its allies in creating the conditions in which Xi's rivals move against him.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCoups d'étatzChinaxForecasting. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aChina.  aChinese government.  aHong Kong protests.  aPredictive.  aRenaissance.  aThomas Friedman.  aXi Jinping.  aargument.  acapital markets.  acollapse.  acoup d'état.  acrisis.  aforecasting.  ahistorical.  anonfiction.  aparty rivalries.  apolitics.  aprovocative.  asociety.  aspeculative.  atrade war.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook pack